The first virtual provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should .
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, with Czech operators offering virtually all services, as are their Western European partners.
However, there is something missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting long.
We have reported on Mobil.cz many times that the Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the Telecommunications Authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why are prices so high in the Czech Republic compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really makes a fight fan.
It may seem paradoxical, as there are three mobile networks in the Czech Republic and a penetration rate of well over 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to slander the fact that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Council Chairman Pavel Dvořák has often contributed to this, having stated in the past that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a great deal of opportunity (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there's another option - a virtual provider.
The introduction of virtual providers into the mobile market in particular led to a significant price decline, to which the traditional mobile operators also had to react.
The Commission has already taken a number of measures to ensure that the Community's financial resources are not used to finance the implementation of the programme.
But it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February we reported on the launch of mobileking in Poland.
In just six months, this provider has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a traditional provider.
They do not need relatively high costs to build, operate and maintain a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually seen as low-cost companies - offering cheap phone calls and text messages, but often accompanied by a less extensive service offering.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good bet to bet on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically targeted at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept to that in Poland could be implemented in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer.'
In the Czech Republic, the mobile operators say, it is unlikely.
But it's almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, it won't be mobile king.
"While we are talking about expanding this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look particularly hopeful.
It will be more likely that Mobilking will enter the market in other countries of our region", Jana Studničková, press secretary of the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz.
It confirmed indirectly that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competitor.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile phone provider has long been expressed by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We have a strong interest in offering our customers not only fixed network but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in negotiations", said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times are coming.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far, this has been surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this time we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market is highly specific compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area", Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefónica O2 told Mobil.cz in a statement.
Other providers also point to the specificities of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds, in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on".
And she adds: "There will be hardly a virtual provider on T-Mobile's network by the end of the year.
We should have a concrete offer at this moment to think in such a short term".
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the best for our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.'
The responsible authorities - Hand in hand with the suppliers
The behaviour of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why should you make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
The strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was probably placed on the T-Mobile company when U:fon was launched.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is a good argument for why you shouldn't allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: 'The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile provider.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new actor would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services.'
In view of this approach, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike the UK and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is the sole proprietorship of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OPC).
But this was his typical attitude to the whole problem.
'The entry of a virtual mobile operator into the market would be possible only after a contract has been concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual provider for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional suppliers,' said Kristián Chalupa of the Foreign Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
The Commission has not yet taken into account the fact that the Commission has not yet adopted a proposal for a regulation on the marketing of certain products.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority that represents the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses their position in the market.
In particular, Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a country where virtual providers operate normally abroad, their market entry has contributed to a decline in mobile phone prices".
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and the reduction of prices are not likely to be in the interests of the OHIM.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the Commission's proposals are implemented in a manner that is consistent with the objectives of the programme.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolute price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly a coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
'The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position and therefore does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their market activities.
The telecommunications regulator is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers,' Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always required for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the mobile operator has - logically - a monopoly on its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if this argument is not accepted, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
A number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) complained that they encountered very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The shifting of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendments to the Telecommunications Act have failed to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competence to the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must be well aware of this, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if no one's looking
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not taken into account.
They are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but they are only partially public.
The Commission has also adopted a number of proposals for a new directive on the marketing of products.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to select individuals.
The funny thing is, the company is acting like a classic business customer to the operator who orders a lot of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases you describe, then it may be a breach of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to the termination of cooperation with the relevant company", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be heard among the responsible operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The Commission therefore considers that the Commission is not in a position to take any further steps to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the measures are implemented in a manner that is compatible with the internal market.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, and yet only a very small percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have full access to it as normal mobile phone customers do.'
But that alone would at least be strange to the CTU.
The Commission has also proposed a new proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment.
The mobile operators are closing their eyes to such an operation, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has fairly strong competence to detect such activities and, if it does not wish to, does not have to satisfy itself with the explanation of the providers that they were unaware of it and that their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasised several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the market has led to a significant price decline in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent them from emerging in practice.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed world, however, it was at this time that regulators intervened, trying to protect the interests of their customers rather than those of mobile operators.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressures, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech authorities are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
In the light of our experience, we cannot escape the impression that in these cases, uncertainty in competence is more than advantageous.
But we're not gonna throw the shotgun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be back on track.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not be inactive in rejecting (discriminating) further interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not be more expensive to use than the rest of Europe.
