The Prague transport companies will also be promoting a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will go down in the history of Prague transport companies as the date when the first passengers to board a subway, tram or bus will carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can be purchased by about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and play it simultaneously on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport operators at the Museum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka subway stations.
The coupons are also available on the Internet on the transport companies' website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used up to the afternoon hours by over four hundred customers.
Those who use the Internet can really forget the ticket window at the subway stations, where they have had to wait in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon online, and it's played on the opencard at one of the 13 branches of the city library.
"In these places, travellers also have a trained staff who can advise them on online purchases and also show the coupon on the card", said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on self-service machines on the opencard, which are installed in some subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, remember ticket values, passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I.P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská subway stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year they will be eighty", Opatrný adds.
The coupon is controlled by an automated machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will be operational from tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is enter the chip card, and the coupon you bought before will play itself out.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, which mainly take inhabitants from communities in the Central Bohemian region to the capital.
"On trains belonging to Prague integrated transport, train attendants have readers to check the validity of coupons by time and zone", explains Filip Drápal of the organisation Ropid, which compiles the itineraries for Prague transport operators.
Suburban buses have card readers at the driver's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked spot on the side of the register.
The driver checks the validity of the coupons played.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons played, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information", Drápal said.
A passenger who does not drive suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon expires may go to the vending machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
The information on the validity of its documents is displayed here on the device's display.
