I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This broad region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
So at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there's reason to believe that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature is likely to be the linguistic nature of man: Since so much of his experience is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, you could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, however it may be acquired, is likely very different from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's hard to tell what consciousness might look like in other animals.
If it is something internal and subjective that cannot be measured or analyzed by our own experience because of the specific hardware, then its research presents us with great problems.
Most of my statements relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible to science.
You could study the processes of consciousness in animals regardless of their contents, and that's exactly what happens in studies of primate short-term memory, especially with the example of visualization.
