Debate on bilingual education: education in an English-speaking environment
In this issue of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California Studies and senior director of the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choices".
Addressing the Hispanic electorate is a complicated task.
The education proposals of Barack Obama are a typical example of this.
Obama's campaign mentions that "the odds of African-American and Hispanic students graduating are lower than those of white students" - which is true.
To close this gap, Obama's education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition phase in education for those who are just learning English.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, conflicts with his interest in reducing school distances.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in East Los Angeles.
The majority of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the pupils, many of whom are newly arrived in the country, are learning English.
Yet in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-graders passed the state math test at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of fourth-year students were rated good on the English test.
This amazing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
Sixth Street School places its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
The school also practices the approach to education in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama should be aware of, according to school principal Linda Mikels.
This approach emphasizes the almost exclusive use of the English language in vocational education.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me that the school had had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico.
"It works", she remarked, "it works for us".
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large percentage of Latin American and other English-language learners?
The school's performance would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within its own party (the national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama's response uncertain.
While he agrees that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the subject by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation that is "English only".
Instead, he said, "You have to make sure your child can speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to close the gap, he should carefully consider models of education that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
