The pride and hardship of the black people's lives in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the outcrops of the Orlando-area amusement parks, a few miles from the glittering, noisy, gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city that reveals the pride and complications of African-American culture.
Eatonville, the first all-black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935. "The city with 5 lakes, three cricket grounds, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison".
Today it's a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city it describes and made a tourist destination by including it in the Florida Travel Guide, produced by the Federal Writers Project during the Depression, is and remains in many ways a place of a very special kind.
Eatonville is as independent, as fit, and as private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what's missing".
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open discussion about race relations, many here continue to get tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We're very careful about how our story is told", says Hortense Jones, 59, a native of the city and a member of the city's oldest church.
It has to be true".
Eatonville has long been defined as the paradox of triumph and struggle.
It's both a historic example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 residents where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a fortress of literature on the one hand and an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It's no surprise that the people here are both proud and cautious.
And so, the concern about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in oral style, such as Mules and Men (1953) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide changed the city, located very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, into the scene of black history and human drama.
Like Oscar in both real life and literature, Hurston Reader led to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private matters.
"To the left of the road", she wrote, "is the brown-white-painted modern school, with its well-groomed gardens and playgrounds, which Howard Miller always tends, though he can barely read or write".
She also mentioned the new man from Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever-ever fits classrooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was definitely not a guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston, quoting men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like this".
Hurtson is still remembered here as a vibrant eccentric who regularly returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to town with a broom, she did so mostly without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today picks up a bit of her respectable dress style.
Mr. Franklin said most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long", he added as he rocked his chair on a back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were stolen.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary of Langstin Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
There was no grand memorial service in Eatonville, no large-scale public reading.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their legacy in the slightest", says Valerie Boyd, author of Wrapped in Rainbows, a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turning point came in the '80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to build a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main road.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western suburbs.
The proposal was made while Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial segregation brought hatred into the community.
"In that time a bunch of white boys often came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away", said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car".
In 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, calling its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "offensive rather than respectful of my race".
Residents today say that while the end of segregation was in some ways positive, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - they hugged their teacher in the morning and they hugged their teacher in the evening", said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group for protecting the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for as long as teachers and students could no longer come from the same place, she added.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural gap", said Mrs Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped to make room for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors, and artists who have moved beyond prejudice, as she did, with positive self-esteem and statements like, "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand that".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out to Hurston's unnamed grave and began to fight for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-lauded Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway was found on bookshelves, and once again made it part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance project came at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the public eye.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a lifesaver.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the freeway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many return every January for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans for a five-lane highway were a major source of excitement for the city, speeding up the process at a high speed, and creating real citizens' pride", said Mrs Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the long-distance project has helped change the city's self-image.
More and more train travelers came, as did Rachel Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a special place in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(She's 90 percent black these days.)
Outsiders seeking the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission and certain things - such as the mural of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their sheltered community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, a higher degree of homeland pride was born.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, no worse or better, and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the city government or the police, who he says may need some help.
And even younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said one Sunday after church.
"But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it's a very beautiful city".
