Hema-Quebec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most of all, it has regained the public's trust, which had been severely shaken by the blood-stained scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the public's discontent, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry in February 1994 led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to develop guidelines to prevent another such disaster.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for administering blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started their work, only 38% of people had confidence in the blood-preservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through work in this area over the following years, we have regained public trust,' she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that 'trust is extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of prudence.
At the time, we saw the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
So we're referring to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which says that you can use exclusion when you don't know it and when a disease progresses slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by brain degeneration, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was accepted from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proven beyond a doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution we have applied has a very good purpose.
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique was introduced: nucleic acid testing (NAS), which allows the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, rather than the antibodies to the virus, as was the case with previous tests.
The NSTs have enabled us to shorten the incubation period between the time the person is infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood using our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
So the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it, and you couldn't tell, was reduced significantly.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of AIDS transmission through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of contracting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, you would have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone could be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood clots annually, it would take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmission to occur through a blood clot.
I believe that you can feel comfortable with a blood transfusion or prescription to restore health these days", says the head of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year did the Chikungunya virus appear on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects through blood.
We must keep an eye on it,' continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate care in addition to safe care.
`The need is increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood supply network, which on average only accounts for 3% of Quebec's eligible blood donors.'
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who donate blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent are excluded from blood donation for one year.
` With this 3% we can get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortage of supplies is very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly, to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find time to spend an hour donating blood,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being inter-storaged at Hema-Québec, which also manages Quebec's only public cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, which was once considered biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
`Weeks ago we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than 1,000 a year.
`We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year,' explains Dr. Décary, who describes this umbilical cord blood-thinning programme as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to this programme', because Hema-Québec lacks the means to offer this complex and expensive programme to all Quebec hospitals.
