Free Speech - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its 17 September issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Vice-General Director of the Canadian gold mine Barrick Gold.
It confirms, and follows an Orwellian logic, that the world's largest gold mining company has sought a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small, unprofitable publishing house in order to open a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge on the truth, especially in cases of defamation, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference has been completely hidden by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to speak up for their opposite opinion.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight an army of lawyers with very unequal weapons, paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal battles are often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual arrangement that will silence the other side and deter anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things to the public.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are usually conducted through the exchange of ideas rather than by a bunch of heists.
So it would have been enough if the Gold Mine had unveiled its books and files and opened up a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and with a handshake, he wipes out the petitions and letters supporting the authors of Noir Canada.
I would like to ask the Commissioner how he can do this.
It seems that in the Vice President's world this word only covers the generously paid lawyers, not the community of all Canadians; a rather narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand -- or doesn't want to understand -- is that the public that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the brutal stance of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a "crazy" lawsuit (in the course of the public debate Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada that they stop using this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom to conduct academic research and to discover the truth, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to research and discuss topics that are not pleasing to the rich companies of the world, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment we belong to has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university community, as well as to the public debate, and it is time for governments to take action to limit this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
