What was produced in the accounting factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On October 8, the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The defendant is charged in particular with being involved in organised crime, gross negligence and business fraud, and other criminal offences, including forgery of documents.
The Prosecutor's Office claims that the proceeds from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often accompanied by counterfeit invoices.
State funds and grants from the local government - a total of HUF 65 million - are to have been partly transferred to the treasuries of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly to private funds.
As the investigating authorities have indicated, the tendering costs were presented with fictitious invoices and the associations were also found not to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were forged.
The bills were bought at the market in Józsefváros, and the circular seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies the invoices should be issued to was taken on that round trip north of Lake Plate to which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
During this "exploration tour", Lados was to locate guesthouses and restaurants.
He requested invoices on consumption to be able to issue invoices for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour and the Budapest Autonomous Government based on these templates.
These bills are alleged to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the drafting of the reports.
One of the goals of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer place.
As two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003 show, the catering company is said to have hosted the 90 member group of Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But now the head of the plant says that such a large group would not have fit into the premises at once.
Another bill, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious errors in form and content.
According to the bill, a boarding house in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than 10 people at a time, has 130 guests.
The imagination of the counterfeiters was apparently not limited to Pigal Kft., a restaurant company whose accounting records of clients Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá do not appear, according to the Prosecutor's Office.
As the managing director Győző Farkas of hvg.hu informed him, he immediately realized that the documents were fake when the prosecutor's office presented them to him during an interview.
"Our company name and tax number were wrong on the stamp".
And furthermore, apart from the mistakes in the form, the fact that the plant was supposed to have housed 100 people was also wrong, after having 11 rooms in total that could not accommodate as many people as possible.
The fact that the bill also mentioned food was a fact that the restaurant had been out of business for a long time.
The embittered counterfeiters also failed to verify that the Budapest Travel Agency they targeted only offered travel abroad and thus indicated Hungary travel on the cash bill, which also contradicted the company's accounting practice.
As the investigation revealed, they also included VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The amount of VAT was incorrect on four invoices issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company was charged only 15% VAT instead of 25%, and the employees only issued machine invoices, but the fake documents were handwritten.
Another error that the 'accounting authorities' made was that they indicated that the service was provided in a case of 'goods transport', although this is not offered by the investment advisory firm, the Prosecutor's Office informed.
Further errors in form - incorrect invoice format, false stamps - were due to the fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and to the XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as counterfeits.
The same was true of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó Sportlager, whose managing directors claimed that they had never issued the invoices.
Another 'mistake' is that the counterfeiters at HIB Kft. in Nyíregyháza were not aware of it: the company was in dissolving itself at the time (2001) when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have eaten there - the public account manager therefore claimed not to have issued the invoices himself.
Consciously forged
The other group of accountants are people who were well aware that they had to put in fictitious bills.
At the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation has issued invoices for the Foundation Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, amounting to approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is also in liquidation, is also said to have cooperated with Zuschlag and Co. In 2003, the GmbH allegedly provided the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület associations with fake invoices totalling HUF 5 million related to unpaid benefits.
However, there was no payment transaction as the invoices were cancelled immediately after they were issued, which the parties forgot to mention in their documents.
The third group of accountants includes persons directly associated with the accused.
One of them is Ivan Kubatov, the Ukrainian postman of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based but not-found fuel and vehicle trading company.
This company is said to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components worth HUF 18 million in total between October and December 2005.
According to the investigating authority, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been liquidated since 14 September 2005, is said to have acted as the buyer of these invoices.
The company was managed by a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be supplied by Ivan Kubatov between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted to having issued invoices on behalf of the GmbH to the Atlasz and Hoppá associations and to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and to having cashed their equivalent.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. are said to have been founded by Romanian sailors at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, in reality none of these companies were active, which the defendant said was due to lack of contracts.
Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was responsible for preparing the company's founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to associations linked to the contract, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is said to have issued 15 invoices totalling HUF 14,2 million on behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade to the organisations.
The Prosecutor General's Office considers that Kubatov could have collected 10% of the invoice sum and VAT.
Kubatov is even alleged to have abused the company Szi-Beri Bt. for the issuance of fictitious invoices - in this case, the invoices were attached to Biztos Pont's applications.
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted their applications to the non-profit organisation of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ('TMA').
Both received forint 500,000 each, but used the sums for an unnecessary purpose.
