The Commission has already made a number of proposals to the Council, which are in line with the Commission's proposals.
The question remains whether this is in his interest, whether the Socialists have concluded a pact with him to compensate for the bulk of the HUF 50 million damage caused and whether the surrogate is willing to take responsibility in return.
But it is quite possible that the "offender" is now being bribed after his demands for relief from detention and house arrest were met with deaf ears.
While other criminals who have done far greater damage with economic offences and have not compensated for them are on the loose, or at least under house arrest, granting is not allowed.
The Psychology of Overpayment - or Why We Are Ready to Pay More
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have now discovered the neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an eBay auction, and are willing to pay even exorbitant prices.
Researchers have tried to explore the neurological pattern of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play lotto while the other participated in a playful activity - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants were able to win money, but increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, where the over-offer of the opponent plays a significant role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the stratum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted additional research to track money.
In this case, three groups should offer against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and then made its own efforts.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward in case they emerged as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis on one group was on winning while the other group was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypotheses expressed by neurologists, the members of the "opposite to loss" group were more willing to bet than those in the control or profit group.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previous economic theory.
The behaviour observed at auctions has hitherto been based on the pleasure of winning or risk-avoiding.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved by the imaging neurological process, so we now have a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is the leading cause of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at 100,000 in this country, but only 7,000 are treated, which is because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver infection and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, through the digestive tract (for example, through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other bodily fluids (such as sperm, saliva or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, but there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and itching.
After that, the yellow fever appears on the skin and eyes, the stool becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people are on medication.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people are unaware of their condition, since the pathogen is subtly destroying liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control checks, is essential.
There are three groups of people who are more likely to develop this disease: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
The number of people with chronic hepatitis C is currently estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to see a family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
If the disease is detected in time, it can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on 30 September, and for the first time in 2004 it was organised by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of the chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers experience less pain?
As recent research shows, religious faith is a kind of "pain medicine" that has already eased the deaths of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: They examined the extent to which belief in God influences people's feelings of pain, reports the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
In fact, a brain scan technology showed that Catholics could activate the part of their brain that regulates pain.
The study was the first in a research project involving philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
In the experiment, the subject was attached to his left hand a sparkling device that gave the electroshocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: one, a 17th-century image of the Mother of God by Sassoferrato, and the other, Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Hermel".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a religious trance among the faithful, while they chose Vinci's image because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as calming.
The subjects spent half an hour each in an MRI scanner, and in that time, they received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages, while they were either looking at the religious or the other paintings.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if "concerned", and they felt "quiet and peace".
While they were looking at the religious painting, they reported over 12% less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was also involved in the experiment, said that you could produce similar effects with other images that were very effective even among atheists, if you just had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find a picture that would trigger very positive feelings, like a mother or a father", says the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases", says Wright.
After these excellent results, the only question remains what effect a Madonna painting by Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain-regularity of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary produce even better results?
You're what you tell yourself
On the occasion of its tenth birthday, Google can rightly say that it is in people's pockets just as much as it is above their heads in the sky: it knows where people have spent their holidays, which doctors they go to, and what moves them.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of Google's CEO.
To the skeptics who are plagued by Orwell's horror visions, he points out that they would just overlook the essence of Web 2.0.
In an interview with the Financial Times recently, Schmidt said that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users and thus get closer to the company's original goal of "ordering all the information in the world".
Schmidt explained that after 10 years of world-changing work, Google is still just beginning to collect information.
When asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google could answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job is really right for me?" but software programs are not yet capable of doing so because they don't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the search terms, IP addresses and pages visited are recorded during their Internet searches.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows the visitor to save and retrieve their own search history, so that the hits can be generated much more accurately later, and the same logic is used to make the so-called "recommendations" that the system uses to recommend tailored products and services based on previous preferences.
However, users wonder what happens in the event of data abuse - "If you look at what I do" - some are concerned about whether Google's data monopoly is there.
In most cases, however, it is the potential power represented by the company that is fear-inspiring, and less so the guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom or the rejection of power that many Internet users finds.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored but also shared with third parties where appropriate, and in these legal cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A recent example of this was the Brazilian anti-pedophilia campaign, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site Orkut, which also allowed the pedophiles to be identified.
However, users concerned about their personal rights were able to catch their breath back in May when Google successfully sued the FBI together with the civil rights organization EFF, so that no constitutional provision could force Google to release information to the FBI at any time in the future.
(The German government, however, successfully obtained the issue of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms in reference to the Law on the Protection of Young People, which was passed years ago, but was denied the list of individual users, or their list of web and search terms, for two months in retrospect.)
Google's image remains controversial: Those who are reluctant to release their personal data because they fear that using Google will lose their privacy and privacy are infuriating the company with the outrage that is due to the companies that claim to be conservative.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is the market leader thanks to Windows, even though both are struggling for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require any identification codes from its users and provides its services free of charge, so an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, geeks are keenly aware of the problematic relationship between personal rights and the Internet - a relationship that has been particularly prominent in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The Web 2.0 is about collaboration, which means that users deliberately leave their tracks and use the available communication channels, and even if the scale varies individually, the main thing remains the same: showing up publicly.
The average teenager can manage his profile on multiple community portals at the same time - from Facebook to Xanga, can link them through other services, such as Twitter, or music services like last.fm, and can finally integrate all of this into a tracking system like FriendFeed or Blip.fm. They can also run blogs that automatically showcase the latest photo galleries that have been scanned on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other examples prove it: looking at the party photos last night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful boyfriend was having fun with, or the employee is fired for just being too honest about his anger about the management of the company in his blog - one thing is for sure: The term "privacy" has been completely reinterpreted by now.
Those who live online are what they reveal - in a way that could form the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And whoever tries to keep something secret, or even bypass Google's monopoly, can do that with pleasure -- like with Scroogle, a tool that can access Google's search engine but intentionally leaves no trace.
Many people don't register on community sites to avoid being found, but Google's online applications, such as word processing and graphics tools and RSS feeds, can also be handled with alternative versions that aren't tied to huge server parks and therefore don't generate the best possible user profile.
But public opinion is waiting until Google shows its true face.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space is threatening advertising revenue, and the increasingly rapidly deployed services are causing head-bursts not only for Microsoft but also for other software developers.
Critics, however, also find the counterpoints worrying: for example, the Group's management completely rejected an employee protest after the company's own kindergarten fees were doubled, and management thought that multiple staff feeding was too expensive, but all this suggests that Google even knelt before the Chinese government in 2006 and agreed to an agreement that all regime-critical hits, or those that violate good taste, would be filtered out.
The Group's internal rules are that no new service is advertised in advance, but only if it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the months and years ahead could again take a big turn: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning or archiving project is now taking the company to the point of having to deal with the Supreme Court, others are more concerned about the 'Health' system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database is already providing the next generation of sci-fi writers with the stuff -- like "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow, which describes in the best of Orwellian fashion a future where a human being is terrifically approachable thanks to data from Google.
