Smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop new accident prevention technologies than to imitate the obstacle sensors that come from nature?
Like the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired Nissan engineers from bumblebees to create new crash-prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C type car-robot-driven biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, to support the development of a system that avoids collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The bee's composite eye, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers adopted the idea of a laser-controlled distance meter.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180 degree field of view within 2 metres, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision avoidance process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of bees, by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it were not for this, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles", explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is currently still considered unavoidable in accidents.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And that's gonna take a fraction of a second.
However, unlike bees, the evasion cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only in the direction of the tire's rotation.
While bees here have endless opportunities to avoid other bees, the researchers at the car robot have been able to use only the rotation, or acceleration, and braking, to do so.
BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it's about instinctive, intelligent response, and less about processing the data, and less about the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and respond to them accordingly.
It doesn't have to store them, or it doesn't have to produce an intuitive, logical response using previous maneuvers, so it only takes a handful of KBs of memory at a time.
It doesn't need gigabytes or megabyte of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the instant collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in series production within the next ten years.
Another application of GPS satellite navigation technology could be to guide the driver around obstacles and to the destination.
