According to the Central Statistical Office, domestic sales prices rose by 0.1% in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9% compared to August 2007.
Export prices were 1.1% higher than in July 2008 and fell by 3.9% from the previous year.
Due to price changes in the domestic and export sectors, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in 2007.
Domestic sales prices increased only slightly, i.e. by 0.1% compared to the previous month.
The sales prices of manufacturing have also increased only slightly - 0.1% - since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was for leather goods (2.8 percent), primarily bags and belts, with 4.6 percent increase, while for shoes prices rose 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials have significantly increased prices for chemicals and manufacturing (1.6%).
Price declines were recorded in crude oil processing (1.4%), electrical and technical equipment (0.9%) and slightly in wood processing (0.1%).
Prices in papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In other branches of manufacturing, a price increase of 0.2 to 0.9 per cent was recorded.
In the main domestic sales markets of industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water, prices rose by 0.3% in August, primarily as a result of the increase in gas prices introduced on 1 July.
The highest increase in crude oil prices (32.4%) was recorded in domestic manufacturing sales in comparison with the previous year.
The metal processing sector saw a 13.2 percent increase, while the food, beverage, and tobacco production increased by 11 percent.
The price decline was observed in the textile industry (2.5%) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3%).
The level of inflation in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6 and 9.1%.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose 10.2% last year.
Electricity, gas, steam and water prices rose by 18.7 percent compared to the previous year.
The highest price increase in the domestic market was recorded in August in the asset sector (0.7%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, while in the energy and processing sectors they remained the same compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was seen in the energy and recycling sector (16.8%) compared to the 2007 comparative period.
In the consumer goods sector, prices increased by 6.8%, while in the investment sector, prices fell by 1.4%.
Industry export prices measured in forint rose by 1.1% in August compared to the previous month, but fell by 3.9% year on year.
