The elite is in danger.
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the House voted against the White House's $700 billion austerity package: a large portion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by the New York Times' report of yesterday's issue, which reported that the crisis is breaking up the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and which wins voters, especially in the south and center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
The above example is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is predicting or even already representing: not only in the United States, but also in the whole of the West and perhaps beyond.
In both the States and Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the rediscovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in conjunction with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis means a decline in banking and financial institutions that have close links to foreign countries and manage a huge amount of the wealth of private households living in a single state.
This is a direct political problem for governments: how to deal with the families affected, who are also a huge electorate.
The crisis is therefore economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have become a thing of the past and lost its right to speak: the EU has given clear evidence of this, which, because of its division, cannot find a common path in various national and international conflicts.
So everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; bailout plans, new rules, and, in particular, the distribution of aid funds: since the crisis has become more serious, only the United States is in the economic position of rescuing itself without foreign aid.
In addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: two conditions which cannot be overlooked under certain circumstances, which no other international organisation or market will be able to use in a similar way.
The new emphasis on the national and state element is in perfect harmony with the increasing importance recently associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is now, when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a connected global realm, a realm of ever-differentiating technologies, of the intangible, that we suddenly have to realize how our future will increasingly depend on the essentially material things: water, harvest and oil.
While these can all be transported from one place to another in the world, they are nevertheless connected to a narrowly defined piece of land  a territory.
The one who has such a territory therefore has an advantage over another who lives in a harvestless, waterless or oil-rich area.
I shall now come to the second novelty, which requires a brief delay.
If you say territory, if you say government, if you say politics, you also say leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to be creating two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there's the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, so the need for someone who knows how to manage things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of resentment over the existing governments, particularly those of the economy, which have emerged as inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, intolerance, a sense of purposelessness, a sense of distance, all directed at a whole class of managers in Western countries.
It seems that the belief among large parts of the population is that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but also their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, that the content of which is increasingly alien and supernatural to the majority.
The demand for leadership, therefore, is underground fueling a branched but powerful movement to undermine the ruling class and the traditional political establishment, manifested in unforeseen "rebels" by voters and the immediate change in the collective mood of recent times: starting with the rise of the Conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
The old elite, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, have become increasingly difficult to understand and therefore less representative of what is happening in the lower social strata of the West today, exacerbated by the financial crisis and driven to the extreme.
In view of all this, it would be simply an exaggeration to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The Super Glue That Lifts Up Walls
To defeat the forces of gravity with a glue and climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now seems to be almost at its destination.
Using a glue that was applied to an area of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers were able to fix a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The study, published by the American journal STUDIO, was the result of research by researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material the team has invented is a further development of the already used adhesives, which use a special carbon structure called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged into a pile of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the feet of geckos, which are covered with microscopic scales that give the animal a perfect grip.
Tests of various materials, such as teflon glass and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the reptile's feet' strength and "can easily be removed from the wall", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a passing adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe they do, but the researchers are thinking of a less fascinating benefit, like connecting electrical devices, because nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in the space sector.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also devoting itself to a new type of glue.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, scientists in California present a glue made of microfibers that cleans itself of dust by moving on a surface like hair, thus maintaining a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in the summer, especially because of their refreshing quality and their high vitamin content, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time as certain essential medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, has repeatedly pointed out the risks of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again raised the alarm: One glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the intake of certain vital medicines to the point where they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of increasing the effects of certain medicines, such as antibiotics, anti-asthmatics, cardiovascular medicines, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
