Open Office, the third version of the "anti-Microsoft" package is coming out.
The day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the open source software is gaining a growing number of users, both at home and in the office, both freelancers and the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft Office.
After a year of intensive work by the volunteer developers supervised by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presented to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now more Spartan-designed start menu, it has finally achieved basic compatibility with Apple's operating system Mac OS x, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest standard ISO version.
The Commission also discussed the compatibility with Microsoft Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read through OpenOffice.
Interestingly, there are also some new features, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes it easier to send via email, including the ability to import PDFs into graphics modules while preserving the original look of the page.
Now, we can also generate "hybrid" PDFs that extend the typical graphics of Adobe to include the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Cooperation is one of the most improved elements of applications: tables can now be edited by multiple users, thus avoiding conflicts when changing; in the case of the word processing system, each editor is assigned a frog to ensure a better correction process.
Some companies are currently publishing various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is expected to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download at the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent home or to the office.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should adopt a proposal for a directive on the protection of the environment and the environment, which is intended to encourage the use of the public procurement system.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which is an optimal aid for small and mediumsized enterprises and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-based text-editing program; Calc, the table program that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for creating presentations like PowerPoint; Dbase, for running databases instead of the more familiar Access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads  a target that can be easily exceeded with 3 million and 600 thousand already reached.
