Student women victims of high rental prices of up to 900 euro per room
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest study by Sunia, the rental union, a single room can cost up to 900 euros a student in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious traits, with whole groups of students losing their right to study in fact because their families are unable to support them at this level", says Laura Mariani, head of Sunia, "and the high demand from students in these cities is leading to a market distortion that has also hurt other residents.
In addition, most rental offers involve a number of violations: free contracts, no registration, no rental price limit, unauthorized sub-leases.
In the case of Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures which, by revising the taxation, lead to lower rental prices.
A closer look at the study shows that in Milan a sleeping area in the Brianza district costs around 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, the average cost of a bed is 350/400 euros, a room is 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the districts around the university, 250/280 euros is needed for a bedside table, 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, prices in the districts around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 euros for a double bedroom.
Rents in the neighbourhoods surrounding the other universities of Rome are only slightly lower: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who escape from outer regions can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples, you need 300 to 450 euros for a place to sleep, and for a room, the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, a bed and breakfast costs 250-350 euros, a single room costs at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater impact on the urban economy.
In cities where rental to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: rents 25-30% above average are demanded by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema. Cities close their historic cinemas.
Historic cinemas are closing due to the advantageous multiplex cinemas.
"A city without a cinema is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
This picture by Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates with effect what is happening in the major urban centres of Italy and also in the provinces.
The process of excluding cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multi-room complexes in the periphery, means in the long run the death of the one-room cinema in the centre, a process that not only seems inevitable and irreversible, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
Most of the time, historical places are filled with memories, "it's like losing a friend who's been on a road full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which won him an Oscar and the Grand Prix at Cannes 20 years ago.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the vast number of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; most of these were in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna, with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is in these three regions that the greatest number of modern cinemas have been registered: with 195 in the last five years, Lombardy is the leader, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "while it is useful that new structures are also emerging, the first priority is the preservation of the existing one, because when a hall is closed in the city, not all its main customers are willing to go to a multi-plex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
The Commission has already adopted a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers' rights in the field of social security.
It is a shame from an ethical and moral standpoint that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to maintain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed.'
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to decide to protect the old cinemas by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas in the historic centre and the periphery.
The measures envisaged include tax advantages for cinema operators and public transport benefits: driving in the restricted areas of the centre and parking at lower parking fees will be allowed.
"It is a pleasant initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow our example and also develop new concepts.
But we certainly need better audio and video equipment to counter the superpower of multiplexing, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been a major issue for me: the closure of the Baghiera Super Cinema, the place of my childhood and youth, was the key point that led me to found Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale on the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to avoid having to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and the 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was ready to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group.
The accusations of the Kalabrien Anti-Mafia Authority's prosecutors against Mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of the municipality of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia business, are serious.
Gioacchino Piromalli, the senior mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew, the lawyer who bears the same name as the clan's boss, were also arrested for their involvement in mafia criminal organizations, and were ordered to pay a total of 10 million euros in damages.
"In defiance of all moral and legal standards", the lawyers write, "the two local administrations decided to pay lawyer Piromalli money for consulting activities".
"This enabled the mafia group to officially infiltrate the council chambers and to participate in the policy of public administration".
The president of the regional committee of Calabria, Agazio Loiero, does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links between local authorities and organised crime".
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who keep a white vest".
The arrests this morning follow those of last July, which the police said were used to decapitate the Piromalli clan.
Since the end of last April, the municipality of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but as early as 1991  and even then, due to alleged links between organised crime and local administration  the local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected as head of the Coalition for Middle-Justice following the May 2006 general election.
He shouted outrage when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the city council.
He accused Deputy Interior Minister Marco Minniti of inventing everything for political and strategic reasons, but the judges explain in connection with the arrest warrant this morning that the Piromalli clan even dared to request a change to the A3 project.
A hearing in connection with the Dal Torrione investigation showed a willingness to respond to the wishes of a businessman who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli, which has made the actions of the public administration identical to the interests of that clan.'
When the energy comes from the waves, suddenly the big ones are running up.
It is a non-perishable source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now do the world's major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, like giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years, and it is no coincidence that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When oil prices fell in 1980, the idea of marine energy was dismissed, but now environmental organizations and the rising oil price are pushing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be met by the energy produced by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there were currents and tides.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies in the traditional energy sector are now relying on marine energy.
"Chevron is exploring these technologies", says a spokesman for a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering working with us".
This is about obtaining approval from the U.S. Energy Commission to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that should not be underestimated, especially considering that oil is still being extracted in Alaska by the United States and that President Bush has just recently started plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; details are not known, but observers are saying there is increasing interest.
We have to make sure that we have the right to make the necessary changes.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far projects like those in Portugal and Scotland are rather small and do not appear to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater environmental impact are needed.
There are several ways: for example, Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via piston and cylinder.
This one drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater pipes.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only awaiting state approval.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The water moves during the tides, which drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational motion.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential customers is already waiting for the necessary authorisations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the waves.
The Institute for Electricity Research says that the potential of tides is of particular interest at the moment.
Although irregular, tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation, and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It's the tidal energy that has driven states like New York, Maine and Alaska, and other coastal states to invest $7.5 million in 2008 -- up to $35 million is already planned for 2009.
